<m0>Retail sales show<ql>
<m4>   LINE 1 IS 4.73 PICA(S) SHORT<m2><ql>
<m0>slow improvement<ql>
<m1><ue5><m4>   LINE 2 IS 3.76 PICA(S) SHORT<m2><ql>
<m4>   TOTAL HEAD DEPTH IS .750 INCHES<m2><ql>
<ql>
<m1><styl>txt,18p<ql>
<styl>crline <m0>From Herald Staff and Wire Reports<ql>
<m1><styl>crline <m0>And Bloomberg Business News<ql>
<m1><ep>
<m0>   Having gotten their Easter shopping out of the way in March, many consumers took it a little easier during April, leaving retailers with mixed sales results for the month.<ep>
   Retail industry analysts, who consider March and April figures together before assessing how well the stores are doing, said sales indicated the overall retail climate is improving slowly after the disaster of Christmas 1995.<ep>
   The big storeowners had widely divergent numbers, with the nation's biggest merchant, Wal-Mart Stores Inc. announcing same-store sales dipped slightly, down 0.6 percent, and No. 2 Sears, Roebuck and Co. posting a big gain (--) 10.9 percent.<ep>
   ``They're all over the fence,'' said Jeffrey Feiner, an analyst with Salomon Brothers Inc.<ep>
   Feiner said unseasonably cold weather nipped into sales. But some apparel retailers, who are particularly vulnerable to the vagaries of the weather, had a good month. Gap Inc., in particular, had very strong sales (--) a 9 percent gain.<ep>
   But Feiner and analyst Terrence McEvoy of Janney Montgomery Scott Inc. saw gradual improvement in the underlying tone of business. McEvoy labeled the numbers decent, with retailers selling merchandise for the home faring the best.<ep>
   The Salomon Brothers retail index, the investment firm's barometer of sales performance, rose 1.3 percent after a 5.4 percent gain in March. In April 1995, the index rose 7 percent.<ep>
   Kmart Corp. reported a 0.2 percent same-store gain. Federated Department Stores Inc. said same-store sales fell 1.1 percent. <m1>  <m0>Sales from stores open at least a year, known as same-store sales, are considered the most accurate measure of a retailer's strength.<ep>
