<m0>Ford challenges Bronco verdict<ql>
<m1><ue5><m4>   LINE 1 IS .66 PICA(S) SHORT<m2><ql>
<m4>   TOTAL HEAD DEPTH IS .313 INCHES<m2><ql>
<ql>
<m1><styl>cxoff<ql>
<styl>txt,18p<ql>
<ep>
<m0>   Ford Motor Co. asked a judge Thursday to overturn a $62.4 million jury verdict against the automaker, charging that two auto safety experts rigged tests to support allegations its Bronco IIs were unsafe. Last October's verdict in Marion Superior Court held that Ford was negligent in the serious injury of two Indiana women hurt in a rollover of the Bronco II, a sport-utility vehicle discontinued in 1990.<ep>
   Ford on Thursday asked Marion Superior Court Judge David Rimstidt to order a new trial, citing allegedly misleading testimony from auto safety experts Dr. Michael Kaplan and Robert Hooker, spokesman Jon Harmon said. <m1>  <m0>Ford accused Kaplan and Hooker of deliberately steering the Bronco II in a way to ensure a rollover.<ep>
   Kaplan on Thursday denied Ford's allegations. <m1>  <m0>He said lawyers in the case used results from prior tests his company had conducted on four Bronco IIs (--) all of which tipped over during emergency maneuvers.<ep>
<m1><styl>hed,18p,18,1,jam<ql>
<m0>P&G, Bankers Trust settle<ql>
<m1><ue5><m4>   LINE 1 IS 1.89 PICA(S) SHORT<m2><ql>
<m4>   TOTAL HEAD DEPTH IS .323 INCHES<m2><ql>
<ql>
<m1><styl>txt,18p<ql>
<ep>
<m0>   Procter & Gamble Co. settled its lawsuit against Bankers Trust New York Corp. over $200 million in losses from derivatives, ending a two-year legal battle.<ep>
   P&G, in a statement, said the settlement includes an agreement to pay $35 million of $200 million it owed Bankers Trust. The bank will absorb the remaining losses, P&G said.<ep>
   ``We are pleased with this settlement and are glad to have this issue resolved,'' said John E. Pepper, P&G chairman and chief executive.<ep>
   Bankers Trust Chairman Frank Newman, in a statement, said the settlement eliminates the last remaining dispute with a client over losses on derivatives, ``and we have done so in a way that serves the interests of all the concerned parties.''<ep>
